Vision of the Artist/Mother: The Strange Creativity of Painting and Pregnancy -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aComing to Life: Philosophies of Pregnancy, Childbirth and Mothering is a superlative collection of essays that does what too few scholarly works have dared: it takes seriously the philosophical significance of women’s lived experience. Every woman, regardless of her own reproductive story, is touched by the often restrictive beliefs and norms governing discourses about pregnancy, childbirth and mothering. Thus the concerns of this anthology are relevant to all women and central to any philosophical project that takes women’s lives seriously. In this volume 16 authors- including both established feminists and some of today’s most innovative new scholars- engage in sustained reflection on the experiences of pregnancy, childbirth and mothering, and on the beliefs, customs, and political institutions by which those experiences are informed. Many of the topics in this collection, though familiar, are here taken up in a new way: contributors think beyond the traditional pro-choice/pro-life dichotomy, speak to the manifold nature of mothering by considering the experiences of adoptive mothers and birthmothers, and upend the belief that childrearing practices must be uniform despite psycho-sexual differences in children. Many chapters reveal the radical shortcomings of conventional philosophical wisdom by placing trenchant assumptions about subjectivity, gender, power and virtue in dialogue with women’s experience. The volume is diverse both in its content and in its scholarly approach; certain of the essays are informed by their authors’ own experiences, others draw from extant narratives; many engage such canonical thinkers as Plato, Aristotle, Nietzsche and Heidegger, while others draw from the works of contemporary feminists including Sara Ruddick, Iris Marion Young, Virginia Held, Julia Kristeva and Luce Irigaray. All readers, regardless of their philosophical training and commitments, will find much to appreciate in this volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Sarah LaChance, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAdams, Sarah Lachance, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurchard, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharles, Sonya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoe, Cynthia D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuenther, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Candace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKittay, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLundquist, Caroline R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLundquist, Caroline R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aManninen, Bertha Alvarez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliver, Kelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRogers, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTuvel, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerhage, Florentien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVernallis, Kayley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiss, Gail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWelsh, Talia, econtributor.